05123nam a22008055i 9780813541044DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20052005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135410447 a10.36019/97808135410442doi  a(DE-B1597)529684  a(OCoLC)77276730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHQ472.E85bI57 2005 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a363.4709400aInternational Exposure :bPerspectives on Modern European Pornography, 1800-2000 /cLisa Z. Sigel. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Issues and Problems in the History of Pornography -- tWanderers, Entertainers, and Seducers: Making Sense of Obscenity Law in the German States, 1830-1851 -- tCensorship in Republican Times: Censorship and Pornographic Novels Located in L'Enfer de la Bibliothèque Nationale, 1800-1900 -- tAnti-Abolition Writes Obscenity: The English Vice, Transatlantic Slavery, and England's Obscene Print Culture -- tThe Rise of the Overly Affectionate Family: Incestuous Pornography and Displaced Desire among the Edwardian Middle Class -- tOld Wine in New Bottles? Literary Pornography in Twentieth-Century France -- tA Perfectly British Business: Stagnation, Continuities, and Change on the Top Shelf -- tGlobal Traffic in Pornography: The Hungarian Example -- tIdeologies of the Second Coming in the Ukrainian Postcolonial Playground -- tStripping the Nation Bare: Russian Pornography and the Insistence on Meaning -- tWalking on the Wild Side: Shemale Internet Pornography -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInternational Exposure demonstrates the wealth of desires woven into the fabric of European history: desires about empire and nation, about self and other, about plenty and dearth. By documenting the diverse meanings of pornography, senior scholars from across disciplines show the ways that sexuality became central to the individual, to the nation, and to the transnational character of modern society. The ten essays in the volume engage a rich array of topics, including obscenity in the German states, censorship in France's Third Republic, "she-male" internet porn, the rise of incestuous longings in England, the place of the Hungarian video revolution in the global market, and the politics of pornography in Russia. Taken together, the essays illustrate the latest approaches to content, readership, form, and delivery in modern European pornography. A substantial discussion of the broad history and state of the field complements the ten in-depth case studies that examine a wide range of sources from literature to magazines, video to the internet. By tackling the highbrow and lowdown of the pornographic form, this volume lays the groundwork for the next surge of studies in the field.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aPornographyxEurope. 0aPornographyxHistoryxEuropexEurope. 0aPornographyzEuropexHistory. 0aPornographyzEurope. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBorenstein, Eliot1 aColligan, Colette1 aLeonard, Sarah1 aMilter, Katalin Szoverfy1 aPhillips, John1 aRomanets, Maryna1 aSigel, Lisa Z., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSlade, Joseph1 aSmith, Clarissa1 aStora-Lamarre, Annie08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813541044.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Ba